 Vega contrasts the vastly different birthing experiences of upper-class and indigenous Mexican women. Upper-class women often travel to birthing centers to be delivered by professional midwives whose methods are adopted from and represented as indigenous culture, while indigenous women from those same cultures are often forced by lack of resources to use government hospitals regardless of their preferred birthing method. Vega demonstrates that women’s empowerment, having a “choice,” is a privilege of those capable of paying for private medical services—albeit a dubious privilege, as it puts the burden of correctly producing future members of society on women’s shoulders. Vega’s research thus also reveals the limits of citizenship in a neoliberal world, as indigeneity becomes an object of consumption within a transnational racialized economy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBirth customszMexico. 0aBirth customs-Mexico. 0aChildbirthxSocial aspectszMexico. 0aChildbirth-Social aspects-Mexico. 0aDiscrimination in medical carezMexico. 0aDiscrimination in medical care-Mexico. 0aIndigenous womenzMexicoxSocial conditions. 0aIndigenous women-Mexico-Social conditions. 0aMaternal health serviceszMexico. 0aMaternal health services-Mexico. 0aMidwiveszMexico. 0aMidwives-Mexico. 0aNatural childbirthzMexico. 0aNatural childbirth-Mexico. 0aWomenzMexicoxSocial conditions. 0aWomen-Mexico-Social conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/31676440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477316788423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477316788/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11